www.iridethemovie.com Since ‘The Wild One’ in the 1950s the world has been fascinated with the mythic culture of the American biker. Who are these people with the loud motorcycles, leather jackets, tattoos, and long beards? Where are they going as they roar through town in large packs? And what do they do when they arrive wherever they’re going? I RIDE is the film that finally tells the true-to-life story of the biker community in America. Through the eyes and music of The Fryed Brothers Band, I RIDE will take you on an illuminating road trip through the biker world: bare knuckle fights you actually sign up for, wild bar-b-ques and camp outs, and partying raw and rowdy at some of the biggest hard core biker festivals. This trip will wind up at Sturgis, South Dakota for a Fryed Brother Band performance to end all performances. The Fryed Brothers Band? They’re the best band you’ve probably never heard of. For 29 years they’ve been the exclusive ‘house band’ of America’s Biker Movement. Every year The Fryed Brothers headline most of the preeminent biker events in America including the Easyriders Show in Sacramento, CA, Rip’s Bad Ride in Irvine, CA, Ghost Mountain Riders Show in Salinas, CA, the Circle of Pride in Iowa, and most importantly, ‘Sturgis Bike Week,’ the largest gathering of bikers in the world, which completely takes over the small town of Sturgis, South Dakota every August to celebrate this outlaw culture. When they were young, Harry and Tommy Fryed’s older brother Mark died in a accident while riding his beloved Harley. The brother’s resolved then to keep Mark’s memory alive through a devotion to the motorcycle culture and the music he loved... and thus was formed The Fryed Brothers Band. The song ‘I Ride’ -- a key song in their repertoire and in the documentary -- is a tribute to their fallen brother. I RIDE, the film, is a tribute to their perserverance, dedication and love of all things biker.

Matt Hotch doesn’t look like a bike builder. A kind smile comes easily to a face that evenly reflects the convergence of his Czech and Vietnamese forebears. Matt doesn’t even have a motorcycle of his own. “If I spend too much time riding,” he laments, “it’s all over. There goes the business!” At least he can hop on any one of his latest creations at a moment’s notice for a shakedown scoot. When it comes to building choppers, he is Mr. Clean. But that doesn’t mean his work is sterile; it seethes with infectious style. His state-of-the-art assemblies, such as switches, wiring, and cables are pathologically inconspicuous.

Maryland State Fairgrounds played host to one of the largest motorcycle shows on the east coast which is known as the Timonium Motorcycle Show (TMS). Even though the festivities take place during the height of winter, it surely looks like summer once you enter the building. Motorcycle enthusiasts, builders, enthusiasts and patrons make the trek to gaze over a cadre of custom sportbikes, baggers, choppers, drag bikes, vintage cycles and antiques of all makes from around the country. With the TMS attendance rising each year, Maryland State Fairgrounds housed over 45,000 showgoers over the 3-day bike festival.

photo.title: 2010 Softail Deluxe, Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine 2010 Had Hell Angels and Bike Enthusiasts Ogling

description._content: The Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine took place on Aug 15, 2010 along Vancouver’s Water Street between Richards and Carall. There were cruisers, sport bikes, fat boys, customs, choppers, softtails, vintage, Euro, Japanese, Americans, rat bikes, tour bikes, sidecars, drag bikes, electric scooters for a sustainable future and more. For $20 or less, you could bring your bike to the show and have judges looked it over to see if yours deserved the first prize. Several manufacturers had their display on site and they made sure that you know who they are and where they come from. Same with some in the crowd. Quite a few wore colors on their vest as well. The Hells Angels, bike enthusiast and causal onlookers rub shoulder with each other and ogled the same thing - motorcycles. Thousands jammed the Gastown streets to enjoy this free event organized by the B.C. Coalition of Motorcyclists that is the biggest annual bike show in town. The only thing you won’t find was the revving noise of the bike engines. This section of Gastown that was once Gassy Jack Deighton’s old haunts was blocked off to traffic completely to facilitate the bike show and to provide limited parking for bikers who drove their motorcycles to the show. [Photos by Ray Van Eng ] www.vancouver21.com

photo.title: Man on a motorcycle and man in a wheelchair

description._content:
This picture has a message.

Last night I was awakened at three in the morning with a haunting thought. There are times when even I amaze myself at how insensitive and selfish I can be. It suddenly struck me that as I was preparing to take this picture of this motorcycle and the man sitting on it, I remember being annoyed because the man in the wheel chair would not move out of the background. Sitting up in bed at three in the morning, the guilt of my selfishness came crashing down upon me. I got out of bed and started up my computer. I took a long, hard look at the man in the wheel chair. He had no legs of course. He wasn’t looking for pity or sympathy. He could be a Vietnam veteran, I thought. He looked to be about my age. His eyes projected that hollow and vacant look of a man who had seen more than what he had wanted to see. Experienced more than what he had wanted to experience. Felt more pain and fear than he had wanted to feel. And there I was so intent upon getting a meaningless picture, being irritated by the presence of what I considered at the time, a “distraction”. If anyone should know that “look” it should have been me. I had seen that look so many times – in Vietnam, in the Hines VA hospital and in my recurring nightmares for many years after. As if this weren’t selfish enough, I realized that although I did talk briefly to the man to whom this motorcycle belonged, I had not bothered to get his name. He was a very pleasant guy and had even offered to take a picture of me sitting on his bike – which I declined. I had asked him if he would sit on his bike while I took a picture to which he very graciously agreed.

Yes, the message is clear now. Whenever I place more importance in “things” over my fellow human beings, I have lost the real meaning of life. Whether the man in the wheel chair had lost his legs in an accident, or because of an illness or in the carnage of the Vietnam War is irrelevant I suppose but being a vet myself, there is a silent brotherhood among all those who served in that terrible war – whether having served in actual combat or as a non-combatant. So not only did I commit the sin of selfishness over all mankind, I might have broken the unspoken rule of “brotherhood”.

No, I am certainly not looking for anyone’s forgiveness or words of empathy. The message is simply this. To myself and all who read this. When a fellow human being holds a door open for you at the local Wal-Mart, say; “thank you”. When a fellow human being lets you out in traffic say, “thank you” and give a wave of your hand. Acknowledge the existence of your fellow man and you will be acknowledged. If someone cuts you off in traffic or allows the door to slam in your face, say “asshole” (under your breath, of course) because there are a lot of assholes (like me) in this world!

In conclusion please look at this photo as a picture of two or more fellow human beings rather than a picture of a motorcycle. I am sorry that I had to ruin what could have been a reasonably good picture of this man’s motorcycle. I blew it. I overlooked the true meaning of life........

This was a really cool project bike I picked up. The motor had been built up with an 836 kit and an electronic ignition. The bike absolutely screamed for a CB. The power increase from these mods is significant. photo.title: 2009 Suzuki M90, Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine 2010 Had Hell Angels and Bike Enthusiasts Ogling

description._content: The Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine took place on Aug 15, 2010 along Vancouver’s Water Street between Richards and Carall. There were cruisers, sport bikes, fat boys, customs, choppers, softtails, vintage, Euro, Japanese, Americans, rat bikes, tour bikes, sidecars, drag bikes, electric scooters for a sustainable future and more. For $20 or less, you could bring your bike to the show and have judges looked it over to see if yours deserved the first prize. Several manufacturers had their display on site and they made sure that you know who they are and where they come from. Same with some in the crowd. Quite a few wore colors on their vest as well. The Hells Angels, bike enthusiast and causal onlookers rub shoulder with each other and ogled the same thing - motorcycles. Thousands jammed the Gastown streets to enjoy this free event organized by the B.C. Coalition of Motorcyclists that is the biggest annual bike show in town. The only thing you won’t find was the revving noise of the bike engines. This section of Gastown that was once Gassy Jack Deighton’s old haunts was blocked off to traffic completely to facilitate the bike show and to provide limited parking for bikers who drove their motorcycles to the show. [Photos by Ray Van Eng ] www.vancouver21.com

Torian Chopper Leathers sponsored the The Horse Smoke Out 9 on June 20-22 in Mocksville, NC at the Farmington MotorSports Park. The SmokeOut is the best show on earth for guys and gals that like an old school biker rally/party/bike show. It’s just plain fun. www.torianmarket.com has your hookup for pics at the show. The Smokeout satisfies the craving for home-built chops, bobbers and creative customs! Old metric cruisers, triumphs and Harley’s don’t die, they get rebuilt into rad chops. This bike show has only one class: CHOPPER. Choppers of all varieties are represented, bobbers, Swedish Chops, Rock-a-Billy Chops, etc. as well as various engine configurations such as Sportsters, metric engines, Shovelheads, Evos, everything. The Smoke Out is host to the greatest ride in owner-garage-built-ride-in-bike-show in the world.

A chopper is a radically customized motorcycle,  a perfect example is the customized Harley-Davidsons seen in the 1969 film Easy Rider. (shown above)

Before there were choppers, there was the bobber, meaning a motorcycle that had been "bobbed," or relieved of excess weight by removing parts, particularly the fenders, with the intent of making it lighter and thus faster, or at least making it look better in the eyes of a rider seeking a more minimalist ride.

photo.title: The D&D Sponsored 2012 69 Chopper @ Ultimate Builder

description._content: The 2012 69 Chopper called Filigree made its debut at the 2011 Ultimate Builder Custom Bike Show in Dallas, Tx. (www.ultimatebuilderbikeshow.com) The chopper was built by Brass Balls Bobbers and sports several world-class components that enhance the handling and performance. The heart of the bike is a custom-built engine by Crazy Horse Motorcycles, primary from Evil Engineering, electrics from Accel, wiring and speedo from Wire-Plus, gas cap, headlight and rear light form Crime Scene Choppers and controls from Excel. The paint is based on the original Brass Balls Tattoo bike where the raw metal was clear coated. Brass Balls used candy blue and pin striped filigree. The paint contrasts nicely with the nickel-plated frame. The bike delivers a soul-satisfying experience and the deep rumble from the 100ci Crazy Horse engine, which makes its presence known through a D&D Bob Cat exhaust system from D&D Performance Enterprises.
